<TITLE> Coasts heighten warning as Bijli nears </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Apr 16 (bdnews24.com)  Ports were asked Friday to raise danger signal 6 as the cyclonic storm "Bijli" gaining strength was closing in on the shores. Lying over north Bay of Bengal, it is likely to intensify further and may cross Barisal-Chittagong coast near Meghna estuary by Friday night, the Meteorology Department said in a special weather bulletin. It was centred at 9am about 490 kilometres southwest of Chittagong port, 460 km of Cox's Bazaar port and 330 south-southwest of Mongla port. Maximum sustained wind speed within 54 kms of the cyclone centre is about 70 kph rising to 90 kph in gusts and squalls. Sea will remain very rough . The coastal districts of Cox's Bazaar, Chittagong, Noakhali, Feni, Laxmipur, Bhola, Barisal and Chandpur and their offshore islands and chars will come under danger signal six. Chittagong and Cox's Bazaar port have been advised to hoist danger signal 6 and Mongla port danger signal five. The coastal districts of Patuakhali, Barguna, Pirozepur, Jhalokathi, Bagerhat, Khulna, Satkhira, and their offshore islands and chars will come under danger signal five. Under the influence of the storm, the coastal districts of Cox's Bazaar, Chittagong, Noakhali, Feni, Laxmipur, Bhola, Barisal, Patuakhali, Barguna, Chandpur, Pirozepur, Jhalokathi, Bagerhat, Khulna, Satkhira, and their offshore islands and chars are likely to experience heavy rain accompanied by squally wind speed up to 120 kph. The low-lying areas of these coastal districts and their offshore islands and chars are likely to be inundated by a storm surge of 7-10 feet above the height of normal tide. All fishing boats and trawlers over north bay must remain in shelter until further notice, the bulletin ad
